    "narration": [
      {
        "start": 0,
        "end": 6,
        "text": "Copy Fail, tracked as CVE-2026-31431, is a Linux kernel vulnerability that lets an unprivileged user get root with a 732-byte Python script."
      },
      {
        "start": 6,
        "end": 13,
        "text": "The attack works by writing four controlled bytes into the kernel's page cache for any readable file, then executing that poisoned binary as root."
      },
      {
        "start": 13,
        "end": 20,
        "text": "What makes it unusual is that it is portable, tiny, stealthy, and cross-container, which are four properties that almost never appear in the same exploit."
      },
      {
        "start": 20,
        "end": 27,
        "text": "The attack runs in four steps: open a crypto socket, build a payload, write it into the kernel's cached copy of su, and execute that poisoned binary."
      },
      {
        "start": 27,
        "end": 34,
        "text": "The recommended mitigation is to blocklist the algif_aead module, but that breaks legitimate crypto functionality, and related vulnerabilities called Dirty Frag and Fragnesia bypass it entirely."
      },
      {
        "start": 34,
        "end": 41,
        "text": "CVE-2026-31431 is patched in mainline, and every major Linux distribution has shipped an advisory, including Ubuntu, Debian, RHEL, SUSE, and Amazon Linux."
      },
      {
        "start": 41,
        "end": 48,
        "text": "A performance optimization added in 2017 broke the page-cache isolation guarantee, and nine years later a 732-byte script exploits that mistake on every distribution."
      },
      {
        "start": 48,
        "end": 54,
        "text": "Check that your kernel package includes the CVE-2026-31431 fix, and drop a comment if you have questions."
      }
    ],
